SUVAT1

The Kinematic Equation for Distance as a Function of Time for Constant Acceleration

For an object under constant acceleration, the distance travelled by that object as a function of time is given by a quadratic formula with respect to time.

s(t) = s_{0} + u t + \frac{1}{2} a t^{2}

where:

s(t) [var. scal. Position, L, m] is the position of the object at a time $t$
s_{0} [const. scal. InitialPosition, L, m] is the position of the object at time $t = 0$
u [const. scal. InitialVelocity, L T^{-1}, m s^{-1}] is the initial velocity of the object
a [const. scal. Acceleration, L T^{-2}, m s^{-2}] is the acceleration of the object
t [var. scal. Time, T, s] is time

